Ad Performance Aggregator - 1GB benchmark
==========================================

Date         : 2026-05-07
Host         : Windows 11 Pro 10.0.26200, amd64
CPU          : AMD Ryzen 7 9700X
RAM          : 32 GB
JDK          : Eclipse Temurin 21.0.11+10-LTS (OpenJDK)
Input file   : ad_data.csv
Input size   : 1,043,304,870 bytes (~995 MB)
Unique campaigns parsed: 50

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Run 1: documented operating ceiling - -Xmx128m
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Command:
    java -XX:+UseG1GC -Xmx128m -jar dist/aggregator.jar \
         --input ad_data.csv --output results

Output (stdout):
    Processing: ad_data.csv
    Written:    results\top10_ctr.csv
                results\top10_cpa.csv
    Campaigns:  50
    Time:       3.15s | Peak heap: 106.8 MB

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Run 2: stress demonstration - -Xmx64m
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Command:
    java -XX:+UseG1GC -Xmx64m -jar dist/aggregator.jar \
         --input ad_data.csv --output results

Output (stdout):
    Processing: ad_data.csv
    Written:    results\top10_ctr.csv
                results\top10_cpa.csv
    Campaigns:  50
    Time:       3.42s | Peak heap: 60.8 MB

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Notes
----------------------------------------------------------------------
- Peak heap is reported by ManagementFactory.getMemoryPoolMXBeans()
  summed across HEAP-type pools (their all-time peak usage).
- The -Xmx64m run completed successfully, demonstrating that the
  streaming + primitive-accumulator design keeps the working set well
  under the documented 128MB ceiling. The ~8% wall-time penalty is the
  cost of more frequent GC cycles when the heap is squeezed.
- Time is the wall clock from start of CSV streaming through writing
  both output CSVs (measured via System.nanoTime() in App.run).
